The tools, the Well-Architected Tool and Trusted Advisor.

The pillars give you the principles; two A-W-S services turn them into practice you can score against.

The A-W-S Well-Architected Tool lives in the console. You define a workload, its name, Regions, and lens, then pick lenses, the A-W-S Well-Architected Framework lens by default, plus specialised lenses for Serverless, S-A-A-S, the Foundational Technical Review, Machine Learning, IoT, Data Analytics, and Hybrid Networking, and you walk through the questionnaire. Each question has options corresponding to best practices, and the unchecked ones become High Risk Issues or Medium Risk Issues, scored per pillar. You add improvement notes, link tickets, and re-run the review every six to twelve months to watch the workload's posture trend. Custom lenses let you encode organisation-specific standards on top of the A-W-S baseline, which is useful in regulated industries where your compliance team has its own list.

Trusted Advisor is the always-on companion. It runs checks across five categories, Cost Optimization, Performance, Security, Fault Tolerance, and Service Limits, and produces a coloured dashboard with concrete findings. The basic tier, free to all accounts, includes seven core checks, chiefly the security ones, root M-F-A, public S3 buckets, exposed access keys, and I-A-M use, plus Service Limits. Business and Enterprise Support unlock the full set of hundreds of checks. And Trusted Advisor can publish to EventBridge, so alert me when a new public S3 bucket appears is a one-rule wire-up. Use them together: the Well-Architected Tool for periodic workload-level reviews, and Trusted Advisor for account-level continuous monitoring.
